The vaccine for COVID-19 is a hypothetical vaccine against coronavirus disease in 2019 (COVID-19).
Although there is no vaccine with the completed clinical tests, there are several ongoing attempts to develop it.
At the end of February 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) said not to expect a vaccine against SARS-CoV-2, a virus causing the disease, to be available in less than 18 months.
Five vaccine candidates were in phase I of the safety studies in April.
COVID-19 was identified in December 2019.
There was a major spread of the outbreak in 2020, leading to considerable research investments and activities for the development of a vaccine.
Several organisations are using genomes published for the development of possible vaccines against SARS-CoV-2.
In April, CEPI, the Innovation Coalition in Epidemic Preparation, stated that the needs for vaccine development are the speed, manufacturing capacity, large-scale development and global access.
In April, CEPI scientists reported 10 different technology platforms being researched and developing during early 2020 to create an effective vaccine against COVID-19.
The objectives of the major platforms that have advanced for Phase I safety studies include:
nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) (stage I developer and vaccine candidate: Moderna, mRNA-1273)
viral vector (phase I developer and vaccine candidate: CanSino Biologicals, type 5 adenovirus vector)
As reported by CEPI scientists in April, a total of 115 vaccine candidates are at the initial stages of development, with 78 of them confirmed as active projects (79, according to the Milk Institute). Other 37 were announced, but with little information available to the public (considered in planning or being designed).
A Phase I-II test performs the preliminary safety and immunogenicity test. It is typically randomized, controlled by placebo and multicentre, at the same time as determining more accurate and effective doses.
Phase III tests typically involve more participants in a control group. They test the effectiveness of the vaccine in preventing the disease, while monitoring adverse effects at the ideal dose.
Of the 79 candidates for active vaccine (confirmed in early April 2020), 74 had not yet been evaluated in human beings (follow-up in pre-clinical research).
